    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1959-08-03T15:10:00-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1959-08-03T15:10:00-05:00" n="293"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d293">
                <head>293. Telegram From the <gloss type="from">Department of State</gloss> to the
                        <gloss type="to">Embassy in Poland</gloss>
                    <note n="0" type="source" xml:id="d293fn0">Source: Department of State, Central
                        Files, 611.93/7–2959. Confidential; Limit Distribution. Drafted by <persName
                            corresp="#p_LLR1">Lutkins</persName>, cleared with the Office of the
                        Assistant Secretary of Defense for International Security Affairs, and
                        approved by <persName>Green</persName>. Repeated to Taipei, USUN, and to
                        London for <persName corresp="#p_CRN1">Clough</persName>.</note>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>Washington</placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian"
                            when="1959-08-03T16:10:00-04:00">August 3, 1959, 4:10 p.m.</date>
                    </dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>123. <persName corresp="#p_BJD1">Beam</persName>–<persName>Wang</persName> Talks.
                    Urtel 172 paragraph 2.<note n="1" xml:id="d293fn1">See <ref target="#d291fn2"
                            >footnote 2, Document 291</ref>. Paragraph 2 asked whether there had
                        been any change in the Navy’s practice of keeping well out in international
                        waters as <persName corresp="#p_BJD1">Beam</persName> had stated to
                            <persName>Wang</persName> on October 25 in accordance with telegram 508
                        to Warsaw of October 23 (see <ref target="#d205fn6">footnote 6, Document
                            205</ref>).</note>
                    <gloss target="#t_FYI1">FYI</gloss>. There has been no change in US Navy’s
                    normal practice of operating well out in international waters as stated by you
                    to <persName>Wang</persName> at 82nd meeting. Standard patrol pattern has in
                    fact been even outside 12 mile zone calculated from assumed Chinese Communist
                    base line. No intention here to alter existing patrol patterns.</p>
                <p>As noted by you most “serious warnings” in June and July have involved
                    overflights of Paracels. These represent regular reconnaissance patrol which we
                    have conducted for many months without eliciting any protests. <gloss
                        target="#t_ChiCom1">ChiCom</gloss> claims to islands have no status and
                    recent “serious warnings” over them appear to be part of broader Communist
                    effort in West Pacific to force U.S. patrol lines back by threats, claims,
                    protests and occasional attacks. Letter follows. End <gloss target="#t_FYI1"
                        >FYI</gloss>.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="strong">
                            <persName corresp="#p_MRD1">Murphy</persName>
                        </hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
